## Introduction

One method to ensure common formatting, both in a single report and between multiple reports, is through the use of Power BI theme files. There is one theme file (*with a ".json" extension*) used per report, and it contains a number of general items which can be accessed via the *Customize current theme* option in the *Themes* setion of the *View* toolbar in Power BI Desktop.

<img width="423" height="654" alt="Image - View Themes Customize current theme" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/906261b9-4ca2-4c3c-9bb3-b4c2bbc8e812" />

There are several excellent resources available online to set all theme components, including:

[Power BI Tips Theme Generator](https://themes.powerbi.tips/themes/properties)
<br>
[POINT. Consulting Power BI Theme Generator](https://themegenerator.point-gmbh.com/en/Home)

<br>

> [!NOTE]
> *While these tools are extremely useful, and both have been used extensively in the preparation of the JSON code fragments in this series, their comprehensiveness can sometimes be overwhelming, and it is with this in mind that a simplified treatment of themes is presented here.*


> [!NOTE]
> *The online theme generators were invaluable during the preparation of the code samples for this series; a resource was not found to aid with the code samples for the recently released ***List Slicer*** and ***Text Slicer*** visuals. The samples presented for these 2 visuals were thus developed by manual trial-and-error only using the JSON theme schema as a reference and are minimal; a more complete treatment is left for future development. For more information refer to the [GitHub repository](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-bi/create-reports/desktop-report-themes#set-visual-property-defaults-visualstyles) provided by Microsoft.*

<br>

In the theme file, we can set many common items, including:

- colours (theme, sentiment, diverging)
- page attributes (e.g., background, size, etc.)
- visual attributes (e.g., background, titles, etc.)

The theme properties available for many specific visual types are addressed in dedicated posts in this series.

<br>

> [!IMPORTANT]  
> *It is recommended that you "follow-along" and build your own theme file from scratch, using the fragments presented herein as examples only as they're released. Remember, these examples are illustrative in nature and are not intended to be "production-ready"; only you can determine which code blocks are desirable for your application or organization.*
> 
> *It is further recommended, as the JSON theme file can be easily edited in any text editor (I find **Notepad++** and **Visual Studio Code** both especially useful), that you experience the update process (change a value, re-apply the theme, see the changes) yourself to get the most out of your theme.*
> 
> *A few common properties that can be aligned among visuals include **fontFamily**, **fontSize**, and **fontColor**; use of the *search-and-replace* function is both simple and can have a significant impact.*

<br>

## 1/2 - Base 1 - Global Colours and Page Attributes

### Name

A Power BI JSON theme is has only one required line, the *name* line:

``` json
{
  "name": "Custom Theme"
}

```
<br>

### Theme Colours

A Power BI theme file also often has a section containing a list of theme colours in an array. Here's an example showing 8 colours listed as HEX codes:

``` json
{
  "dataColors": ["#0B31A5", "#0641C8", "#0050EB", "#0078ED", "#008CEE", "#009FEF", "#46B3F3", "#8BC7F7"]
}
```

<br>

### Sentiment Colours

A Power BI theme file can also list sentiment (good, bad, neutral) colours as *key:value* pairs.

``` json
{
  "good": "#00FF00",
  "bad": "#FF0000",
  "neutral": "#FFFF00"
}
```

<br>

### Divergent Colours

Divergent colours are used to represent a data range on a colour scale (i.e., a gradient), and often range from light (lowest) to dark (highest), and are also listed as *key:value* pairs.

``` json
{
  "maximum": "#118DFF",
  "center": "#D9B300",
  "minimum": "#DEEFFF"
}
```

<br>

### Page Attributes

The Power BI theme file can also be used to set a number of page properties (e.g., size, background colour, etc.) in the *visualStyles\page* section.

``` json
{
  "visualStyles": {
    "page": {
      "*": {
        /*  NOTE:
        The page size syntax, although correct below, is not currently taken into account and used
        by Power BI Desktop as of version 2.144.1155.0, June 2025.
        */
        "pageSize": [
          {
            "pageSizeTypes": "Custom",
            "pageSizeWidth": 1600,
            "pageSizeHeight": 900
          }
        ],
        "displayArea": [
          {
            "verticalAlignment": "Middle"
          }
        ],
        "background": [
          {
            "color": {
              "solid": {
                "color": "#F0F0F0"
              }
            },
            "transparency": 0
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}

```

<br>

As an alternative, instead of a background colour, you can use an image as your page background. Simply encode your image of choice as a Base64 image and add to the ***url*** key:value pair. Here's an example:

``` json
{
  "visualStyles": {
    "page": {
      "*": {
        "background": [
          {
            "image": {
              "name": "Space",
              "scaling": "Fit",
              "url": "data:image/jpeg;base64,"
            },
            "transparency": 50
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}


```

<br>

### Visual Attributes

The Power BI theme file can also be used to set a number of global visual properties (e.g., container shape rounding, background colour, transparency, padding, shadow, titles, etc.) in the *visualStyles\\** section; these properties are discussed further in a dedicated post in this series.

Each visual uses a consistent syntax pattern:
<br>
``` json
{
  "visualStyles": {
    "<visualName>": {
      "<stylePresetName>": {
        "<cardName>": [
          {
            "<propertyName>": "<propertyValue>"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}
	
```
<br>

From [Microsoft's document](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/power-bi/create-reports/desktop-report-themes#set-visual-property-defaults-visualstyles) on the visual styles:

- For the *visualName* and *cardName* sections, use a specific visual and card name. 
- The *stylePresetName* can either be an asterisk ("*") to target the default visual style, or the *stylePresetName* can be a name to define a named style preset. 
- The *propertyName* is a formatting option, and *propertyValue* is the value for that formatting option.

<br>

> [!NOTE]
> *For complete information on the design and syntax of the Power BI theme file, refer to the [Microsoft website](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-ca/power-bi/create-reports/desktop-report-themes#report-theme-json-file-format).*

> *A known open issue has been noted for the canvas size in the JSON theme file not being taken into account by Power BI Desktop:
